The answer is simple, lacks the competition that would really want to start the fight.
Perhaps it sounds absurd, even here we have three mobile networks and coverage high above 100%.
On the other hand, mobile telephony operators like to feel that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense he often emphasizes also the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTU), Pavel Dvořák, who in the past once said that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It may be true that the traditional operator with its network is not likely to have many possibilities anymore. (The rest may be difficult to find now other frequencies).
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
The entry into the market of virtual operators has led to a significant decline in prices, to which traditional operators would then have to react.
At the same time even before the entry of quali like Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile in the market, there were voices like us in Britain.
However, it has been shown that there is a place for such operators and that they can really succeed.
At the end of the accounts for the examples, we must not go too far.
In February of this year, we informed you of the arrival of the Mobilking virtual operator in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator has managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group to which in the Czech Republic belongs among the other U:phone.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to be able to work effectively, many less customers are sufficient than a traditional operator.
They are not behind, i.e. relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators usually present themselves at low cost, offer calls and SMS at low price, which is often in balance with the offer of the most restricted services
