Talk in your sleep
Some kids talk during the night.
I am not referring to those who are very excited to tell us something that happened to them the previous day, but to those children who speak are still asleep.
The first time that happens, there is a fear at most, but it really doesn't matter much.
This is a slight change in the sleep defined as sleepy sleep.
It is manifested with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Of course, most of you have been told that you spoke in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadicly (once in life, for example, associated with a high fever episode) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child remembers nothing more.
There is no single reason to explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes episodes are related to other sleep disorders such as incubation, night fear, night enuresis (to make the sleeping pipe), or somnambulism, but not necessarily so.
As previously noted, it can be associated with very high fever levels, with stress situations or overcrowding.
In any case, it is a still not studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It may happen that the person speaks with a very quiet voice tone, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite occurs (sigh, yell, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, you should observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to see if there are any issues that are generating an abnormal state of anxiety as an outcome to the situation.
We have said that this is a benign change, so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (e.g. if combined with insomnia or stress).
What can be done, however, is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to bed.
Offer quiet games and avoid programs or television series that cause fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is easy to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more quietly.
Once the dreams appear, try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the day after it will remember nothing of what has happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
It's useless, because it's not aware of what's going on, and you've interrupted his sleep.
Though he's talking, he's sleeping and he's resting.
