Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday's tenth anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, as Hema-Québec became one of the most secure and effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, he regained public confidence, seriously removed from the blood scandal infected in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such a drama and the protests of the population, the Government of Canada conducted a public investigation in February 1994 , led by Judge Horace Krever, which sought to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the recurrence of a similar disaster.
While Judge Krever was delaying a report, some provinces set up a committee to devise a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Québec started its activities, just 38% of people said they still had confidence in the donation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalled.
The situation was deadly.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve the safety of blood collection and field research over the years, we have regained public confidence," he said, before saying proudly that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of Quebec's population had now trusted in Hema-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were many cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob, who tells her that it is to the presidency since 1998, the year of the foundation.
"And we didn't know at all if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
So it was based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports that when you have doubts and could get a serious illness, in this case the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob, which occurs with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, will be taken into account.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than one month in the United Kingdom was refused.
Now, for a few years, it has been proved that no doubt this disease is transmitted through infected blood.
This episode so proved to us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for the identification of HIV appeared on the market: tests of nucleic acid (TAN) that allowed direct recognition in donor blood of the presence of the virus and not of antibodies against it, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have allowed to reduce the window period, since the person contracted the disease to the one where the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
That period could be reduced to less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and not being able to identify them is thus significantly reduced.
These improvements have made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of countering AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one out of 12 million people are at risk of receiving blood infected with HIV.
"In other words, this means that it will be necessary to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Hema-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years to meet a case of HIV transmitted with a transfusion.
I think that today you can feel calm in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to restore health, says the Head of the Hema-Québec Directorate.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogen will come out of the system.
Not later than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the Réunion Island that, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
Hema-Québec must also provide sufficient resources in addition to having safe resources," continues Dr. Décary.
"Necessity increases because the population is ageing.
Being the cure against the most aggressive cancer, patients often need a contribution of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences on the number of donors that on average account for only 3% of Quebec's inhabitants are eligible as donors."
However, all healthy people who are 18 years of age and who meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of the people offering themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they travel in a country where the latter is disseminated, they will be refused for a period of one year.
"With this 3% we are able to maintain an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
Poor cases are very rare.
But we need to renew the members of this group of donors as they age and can no longer make donations.
Now it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to hold it and encourage it to become regular donors.
Today's life is so frenzy that it's difficult to give blood an hour," said deplored Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissues, of which bone transplants, heart valves eyeballs and skin that are used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being deposited with Hema-Québec, which manages the only public bank of ombelic cord blood in Quebec.
In the umbelic cord, which once was considered a biomedical waste, there is plenty of blood rich in stem cells that can help cure serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the insertion into the bank of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we expect to take more than a thousand each year.
It should begin with proposals for transplanters at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this practice of taking cord blood as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that you cannot have access," because Hema-Québec does not have the means to propose this complex and expensive program in all Québec hospitals.
