The psychology of excessive bidding: why spend more money?
At the auctions, buyers are willing to spend more, to overvalue the goods.
Researchers neurologists and economists at the University of New York have been able to discover the neuro-economic bases of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published on Science magazine, men do not want to stay back in a race such as eBay auction, so they are also available to pay a higher price.
The research has tried to trace the nervous scheme of this "party" at the level of the nervous system through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, the other group of players participated in an auction while using the functional magnetic resonance method (fMRI) examined the active areas of the brain of the participants in the experiment.
In both games the participants could win money, but in the auction game, in which the substantial element is to bid more than the other, the cortex stretched under the brain enter into force intensively when you lose the game.
This brain area, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the "autogratification" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to researchers, the rise in the price is explained by scanning the actual reaction of the stretched body.
To support their theory, the economists of the research group conducted a financial investigation.
In this investigation, three groups have tendered against a partner under different conditions.
The control group reported the actual value of the product concerned and made them their point.
To another group, they promised that in the event of a win, they would receive another $15 prize.
The third group would have received $15 before the auction, but the members of the group would have lost money in the event of a loss to the auction.
The difference between the two groups was the fact that for one of them the win was highlighted, while for the other the loss.
Testing the hypothesis of neurologists the members of the group who played "against loss" were willing to make higher points than the control group or "win".
"These results are not deductible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
In fact, these so far explained the phenomena encountered in auctions with the joy of winning and with the avoidance of risk.
Only the methods of creating the neurological image helped resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so that we came to a third explanation" - said Andrew Schutter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when do you talk to your doctor?
Almost half a billion people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, but chronic liver diseases are mentioned in Hungary among the first causes of death.
In Hungary, the number of hepatitis patients increases to 100 thousand, of which only 7000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know how to be infected.
The definition of hepatitis is the collective name of infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities between symptoms, typical are hepatitis and heresy, but their pathogens and the diseases caused differ.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the food channel (e.g. water and infected foods), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal loss, saliva).
For those travelling it is useful to immunize against virus A and B, against C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After forming yellow spots on the skin and on the white of the eyes, the faeces become clear and dark urine, the healing takes place within two to three weeks.
One million people die every year all over the world for hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver tumors and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason, according to estimates, is that only one person in ten receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have very serious consequences: if it is not treated it may cause liver cirrhosis and liver tumours.
Most infected people do not know that they have contracted the disease because the pathogens subtly destroy the liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to prevent and conduct regular medical analyses.
This disease is much more common than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, the drug addicts and the tattoos.
In today's world, the number of people infected by chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Because even a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease is worth addressing the family physician when any symptoms of unknown origin are noted.
Recognized in time the disease is curable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, so it stops the infectious power and can prevent the formation of tumors.
September 30 is the World Day of Hepatitis, first organized in 2004 worldwide by disease associations.
The aim is to draw attention to the chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and early recognition of the disease.
Who believes in God feels less pain?
According to a recent survey, religious faith works as an analgesic species that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at Oxford University have carried out an interesting experiment, examining how faith in God influences the feeling of pain, British Telegraph reported.
In the context of a rather strange investigation, an electroshock was carried out to 12 Catholic believers and at the same time atheists, while all those who observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
Based on the results, Catholic believers were able to reject much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploratory technique of the human brain, it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for controlling the pain.
The test is the first of a series of research in which, in addition to academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians of the University also participate.
The test took place exactly this way: an instrument that emits discharges and passes the electroshock was connected to the left hand of the subject of the experiment.
The researchers asked the participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the 17th century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with the Emmelino by Leonardo da Vinci painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary originated a sort of religious state among the believers, while Leonardo's picture was chosen because it was not too different from the other and they thought it was a calming effect.
The subjects of the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and in this time period they received 20 electroshock in four consecutive series, while observing either the painting on a religious theme or the other.
The Catholics have reported that the vision of the Virgin Mary made them feel "safe", as if "someone would take care of" them and "they were calm and were overcome by peace".
Looking at the image on a religious basis, they accounted for 12% less pain than they had before Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that such a result can be achieved with any image from the strong effect even for atheists, but you need to find the appropriate image.
"We need to look for an image to which they nurture very positive feelings, such as a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
