The Smart Machine Imitates the Flight of Calabron
What could be the best way to develop anti-inflammatory technologies if you do not imitate the sensors of the obstacles that are in nature?
For example, the bees.
In the amazing project presented to the CEATEC in Japan, the calabrons gave the initial strategic tip to the engineers Nissan on how to build the next generation of antillition systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotized mine with the properties of bees, with the goal of creating a system capable of scanning all collisions.
Flying the bees form their own oval personal space that looks really much like our protective shield - it explained to Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR technology and research and development.
Important is the role of the ape view, capable of a 300 degree visual in each direction.
The engineers have focused on the idea of telemetric laser to copy the function of the monkey view.
The BR23C detects the obstacles up to two metres away within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately transforms it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the monkey, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels of the measure necessary to avoid the incident.
This avoidance maneuver, unlike the current system, is carried out in an instinctive manner.
"If it weren't for that, the auto robot wouldn't react quickly to avoid collisions" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the auto robot project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the harmful and more internal layer of the protective shield, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in an eyeball.
But unlike bees the deviation cannot go up or down or in diagonal, it can only be bidimensional and in the direction of wheel steering.
In this way, instead of the endless possibilities available to bees to scan the other bees, the robot, as available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by batteries to lithium polymers, lighter and with high energy density, which means that their duration is higher than those to lithium ions.
According to Andoh, the instantaneity of the intelligent reaction is important, not the processing of data or even less the ability to store data.
This robot must produce some inputs in a few seconds and react.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on the previous maneuver data, so it only uses a memory of a few decades of Kb.
There's no need for a gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions that, they predict to Nissan, can be installed on serial vehicles within 10 years.
Further application options can be represented by the unification with GPS satellite navigation system which, by avoiding obstacles present on the road, leads to destination.
