"Most young Roma do not have an average degree of study and as a result of elementary quality teaching only a illogical number of them can reach a higher degree of study".
Járóka also stressed, as a fundamental human right, the key role of education in the enjoyment of human rights.
Investing in Roma children's education can mean strengthening the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the honourable Member it is necessary to make these links more widely known between the Roma and the non- Roma.
The more a Roma start school, the more they are able to become a productive member of the labour market; the more income taxes and consumption are contributing to the nation's budget.
"The right to European citizenship of the Roma must guarantee their right to quality education and the elimination of low-level and segregated schools" - Lívia Járóka stressed.
According to the honourable Member, the purpose and action of the European Union is to speed up the process of deregulating schools and therefore it is essential to respect the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives correctly.
"The visual circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be interrupted, it is necessary to give Roma children the opportunities granted by the democratic space so that they can contribute as citizens full of the future of Europe" - Járóka asked.
As part of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities" to be guaranteed for all, the aim of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities organised each year, since the Berlin Summit last year, is to provide a single forum to promote the objectives of anti-discrimination and equal opportunities set at national and European level.
