"From the scientific findings - the responsible Ue continues - there is a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
What matters most is that we need to raise awareness of consumers and make this information public.
We must also review existing control systems, in the light of this scientific opinion, in order to ensure that they are fully effective and that they take the step of the new technology."
Brussels had asked the independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the large use of portable musical instruments and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise from them.
"Scientists - executive Ue concludes - confirm that there is a cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine, together with the Member States and stakeholders, what measures could be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical devices and similar equipment."
At present, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical equipment to 100 dB, but concerns about the hearing damage that may result from an excessive exposure to these sources of noise are growing.
It is possible to limit many of these damage by resorting to solutions such as reduction of levels and duration of exposure to noise.
In its opinion, the Ue Scientific Committee notes that users of portable musical equipment if they listen to high volume (over 89 decibels) music for only 5 hours per week exceed the current limits for maximum permissible noise at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in these conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity after a period of 5 years.
This would be 5-10% of the users of these devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 million and 10 million people in the EU.
